text.tspan: Two genomic locations on the same chromosome may interact in two different relative orientations.
For the one case, here referred to as simple loop, the intervening DNA forms an uneven number of loops
so as the ligation junctions are either between the inner or outer ends of the two restriction fragments.
On the sequencing level, this results in inward or outward pointing read pairs only.
For the second case, here referred to as twisted loop, the intervening DNA forms an even number of loops
so as the ligation junctions are either between left or right ends of the two restriction fragments.
On the sequencing level, this results in read pairs for which the two reads point in the same direction only.
Self-ligation must result in simple loops and thus inward or outward pointing read pairs, whereas twisted
loops or read pairs are unaffected by self-ligation.
Diachromatic uses this fact to determine a size threshold for self-ligation which is defined as the
average size of all twisted read pairs plus two standard deviations.
Furthermore, simple and twisted read pairs are counted separately for given interacting pairs of restriction
fragments, and if one of the two categories predominates the interaction is considered as directed and
Hybrid fragments from valid Hi-C and cross-ligation
Hybrid fragments from valid Hi-C and cross-ligation
The restriction digestion of cross-linked chromatin results in fragments, also referred to as digests, whose ends correspond to cutting sites of the chosen enzyme. The
digestion may be incomplete, for instance, due to inaccessibility of DNA. Therefore, cutting motifs may also occur within digests. Different digests may be cross-linked
Re-ligations between digests within cross-linked protein-DNA complexes result in intended Hi-C fragments that consist of pairs of digests arranged in linear order and
linked by ligation junctions. If both ends of a given digest pair re-ligate, the product forms a ring with two ligation junctions. The ends of digests from different
protein-DNA complexes may also ligate, which is referred to as cross-ligation. Those unintentional ligations lead to false positive predicted interactions, because the
resulting fragments cannot be distinguished from valid Hi-C fragments. It may also happen that the ends of given digests remain un-ligated or ligate among each other
thereby forming rings, whereby the latter is referred to as self-ligation.
Shearing re-linearizes ring-shaped re-ligation products and introduces additional types of fragments that may have all possible combinations of ends that were either
introduced by restriction digest or shearing. The size of fragments originating from genuine interactions or cross-ligations cannot be deduced from the distance
between the 5' end positions of the mapped read pair as usual , but requires the consideration of restiction enzyme cutting sites.
For fragments that contain exactly one occurence of the cutting motif, the size can be unambiguously deterimed.
This can be achived by adding up the two distances between the 5' end positions of a mapped read pair and the next cutting motif occurences in the reference
However, for fragments containing more than one occurences, it cannot be determined which occurence corresponds to the ligation junction.
